{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473468"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:08:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:08:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2461"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2461"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.31,0.07,0.5,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81701"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2461"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67000"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"318"},{"type":"tags","id":"1058"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2838"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44817"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81701"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with generalised urticaria, red eyes, and feeling unwell. He reports eating a homemade wafer containing unknown ingredients 20 minutes ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he initially appears well. His pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 119/81 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 100% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. During assessment, he deteriorates rapidly with pulse rate increasing to 110/min, blood pressure dropping to 90/64 mmHg, respiratory rate increasing to 30/min, and SpO2 falling to 86%. He is moved to the resuscitation bay, commenced on supplemental oxygen, and intravenous access is obtained.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate adrenaline (epinephrine) dose and route?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1 mL of 1:1000 solution intravenously","1 mL of 1:1000 solution intramuscularly","0.1 mL of 1:1000 solution intravenously","0.5 mL of 1:1000 solution intramuscularly","10 mL of 1:10,000 solution subcutaneously"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with anaphylaxis, characterised by rapid onset of multi-system involvement including cutaneous (urticaria), respiratory (hypoxia), and cardiovascular (hypotension) manifestations following exposure to a likely allergen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.5 mL of 1:1000 solution intramuscularly\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct dose and route for adrenaline in anaphylaxis for this age group. The dose for children is 0.01 mL/kg of 1:1000 solution up to a maximum of 0.5 mL, given into the anterolateral thigh. At 16 years old, this patient would receive the maximum dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1 mL of 1:1000 solution intravenously\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as intravenous adrenaline should only be used in cardiac arrest. The dose is also too high for initial treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1 mL of 1:1000 solution intramuscularly\u003C/strong\u003E represents double the recommended maximum dose and could cause dangerous side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.1 mL of 1:1000 solution intravenously\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the intravenous route should be avoided outside of cardiac arrest. This dose would also be insufficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E10 mL of 1:10,000 solution subcutaneously\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as subcutaneous administration has unreliable absorption in shock states. The concentration and volume are also inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the initial dose, the patient should be reassessed every five minutes and the dose can be repeated if there is inadequate response. Other important aspects of management include positioning (supine with raised legs if hypotensive), high-flow oxygen, and fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intramuscular adrenaline is the first-line treatment for anaphylaxis, given in the anterolateral thigh","The dose of adrenaline for anaphylaxis in children is 0.01 mL/kg of 1:1000 solution to a maximum of 0.5 mL","Intravenous adrenaline should only be used in cardiac arrest"],"references":["Anaphylaxis. In: The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Anaphylaxis/.","Adrenaline (Epinephrine) Injection 1:1000 for Anaphlyaxis. In: Electronic Medicines Compendium (EMC) [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.medicines.org.uk/emc/product/3449/smpc#gref."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67000"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2461"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67000","links"